title: Fee-for-service tied to more low-value surgery rates: Study - Becker's ASC
description:
How surgeons are paid may meaningfully influence how often patients receive low-value outpatient surgery, with fee-for-service environments linked to higher rates of potentially unnecessary procedures, according to a study published Dec. 2 in JAMA Network Open.
Fee-for-service care was strongly associated with higher low-value surgery rates.
Low-value surgery is declining, but the reduction was much stronger in salaried care.
From 2016 to 2019, private-sector care had 29% higher odds of low-value surgery relative to direct care.
The study focused on elective outpatient procedures that have well-defined literature identifying low-value scenarios, especially when performed “alone” in certain age groups.
text:
How surgeons are paid may meaningfully influence how often patients receive low-value outpatient surgery, with fee-for-service environments linked to higher rates of potentially unnecessary procedures, according to a study published Dec. 2 in JAMA Network Open.

Researchers from Boston-based Harvard Medical School and the Uniformed Services University of the Health Sciences in Bethesda, Md., analyzed TriCare claims from the U.S. Military Health System from 2016 to 2023, comparing outcomes across 304,908 outpatient elective procedures performed in the system’s salaried “direct care” facilities or in private-sector civilian settings reimbursed under fee-for-service.

1. Fee-for-service care was strongly associated with higher low-value surgery rates.

Across 304,908 outpatient procedures in the Military Health System from 2016 to 2023, low-value surgery occurred at a much higher rate in the private-sector fee-for-service setting than in the salaried direct care setting. Overall, 35% of private-sector procedures met low-value criteria, compared with 20% in salaried direct care. After adjusting for case mix, procedures done in the private sector had 41% higher odds of being low value.

2. Low-value surgery is declining, but the reduction was much stronger in salaried care.

The study found that low-value procedures fell across both environments between 2016 and 2019 and between 2020 and 2023, suggesting a broader systemwide shift toward tighter surgical appropriateness. Of the 98,150 low-value procedures identified, 56% occurred between 2016 and 2019, versus 44% between 2020 and 2023. In adjusted models, low-value care dropped more sharply in salaried direct care than in the private-sector FFS environment.

3. The private-sector disadvantage persisted, and may be widening, across both time periods.

Even when broken into two eras, outpatient procedures performed in the private sector consistently had higher odds of low-value surgery compared to direct care. From 2016 to 2019, private-sector care had 29% higher odds of low-value surgery relative to direct care. From 2020 to 2023, that gap widened: private-sector procedures had 55% higher odds than direct care in the same period.

4. The procedures examined are common ASC lines and already high on payer scrutiny lists.

The study focused on elective outpatient procedures that have well-defined literature identifying low-value scenarios, especially when performed “alone” in certain age groups. The most common procedure was partial meniscectomy, accounting for 42% cases, followed by acromioplasty, with 29% cases. Overall, 32% of procedures met low-value criteria, including large volumes in high-throughput orthopedic categories.

5. Payment reform alone will not eliminate low-value surgery

Even in the salaried direct care environment, 1 in 5 procedures met the study’s low-value criteria, showing that incentives are important but not the only driver. The authors cite variation in physician beliefs, patient preferences, clinical uncertainty and clinician-induced demand dynamics as contributors to unnecessary procedures.

text:
Facility Coordinator

Pleasantville, NJ

Description

Are you pursuing an exciting career in EMS? Do you want to make a difference in your community? TriCare Medical transportation is now hiring Facility Coordinators. Apply to join our growing team today!

TriCare Medical Transportation is South Jersey’s premier medical transportation company. We are a large-scale 24/7 operation with over 300 employees and 130 vehicles, providing service from our headquarters in Pleasantville, NJ and two satellite locations in Vineland and Cherry Hill.

WHAT YOU’LL DO

As a Facility Coordinator, you will be a key player on our Billing team.

• Answer high call volume in a professional and courteous manner

• Schedule trips for clients that require transportation to and from medical appointments

• Collect trip data and transcribe information through our scheduling system

• Maintain accurate records and monitor workflow for scheduled appointments

• Secure payment for all scheduled patients trips prior to receiving services

• Obtain insurance verifications and authorizations

• Schedule, reschedule and cancel trips as necessary

WHAT YOU’LL NEED

• Availability to work Monday – Friday 12pm – 8pm

• Proficient computer skills

• Excellent communication skills

• Experience dealing with major insurance companies and patient scheduling is preferred

• Ability to work in high pressure situations

• Clean background check

• Negative drug screening

PERKS

• Benefits package (Medical, Dental & Vision Insurance) Medical Benefits starting at $10.00 weekly

• Paid time off (PTO)

• 401(k) after 6 months of service

• Paid training and certifications

• Opportunities for growth and advancement

• Annual increases

• $ 5000 Tuition Reimbursement available

JOB TYPE: Full-time $17.00hr - $18.00hr

TriCare Medical Transportation is an Equal Opportunity Employer

title: Agile Decision Sciences awarded $13.2M contract from Defense Health Agency - 256 Today
description:
WASHINGTON — Agile Decision Sciences of Huntsville has been awarded a $13,271,550 modification under a previously awarded contract, the Department of Defense announced.
Themodification exercises an option to continue administrative, analytical, and consulting services to support, analyze, and investigate issues related to military public health, force health protection, and health service support during deployments, extended training missions, and operational testing, according to a DoD news release.
Services include management, planning and execution support; studies, analytical, and evaluation support; administrative support; document and records management; business process reengineering; logistical support; budget planning and management; knowledge management; and business office support.
Supported organizations include the deputy assistant secretary of war for health readiness policy and oversight; principal deputy assistant secretary of war for health affairs; office of the assistant secretary of war for health affairs; the director, Defense Health Agency; the Chief of Staff; and other subordinate program directorates.
The Defense Health Agency, Professional Services Contracting Division, Falls Church, Va., is the contracting activity.
text:
WASHINGTON — Agile Decision Sciences of Huntsville has been awarded a $13,271,550 modification under a previously awarded contract, the Department of Defense announced.

Themodification exercises an option to continue administrative, analytical, and consulting services to support, analyze, and investigate issues related to military public health, force health protection, and health service support during deployments, extended training missions, and operational testing, according to a DoD news release.

Services include management, planning and execution support; studies, analytical, and evaluation support; administrative support; document and records management; business process reengineering; logistical support; budget planning and management; knowledge management; and business office support.

Supported organizations include the deputy assistant secretary of war for health readiness policy and oversight; principal deputy assistant secretary of war for health affairs; office of the assistant secretary of war for health affairs; the director, Defense Health Agency; the Chief of Staff; and other subordinate program directorates.

The award obligates fiscal 2026 operations and maintenance appropriations for services through Dec. 6, 2026. The total value of the contract, including unexercised options, is $73,187,618.

The Defense Health Agency, Professional Services Contracting Division, Falls Church, Va., is the contracting activity.

title: What You Need to Know About TRICARE Open Season - AAFMAA.com
description:
TRICARE, a comprehensive healthcare program available to active and former servicemembers and their families, is offering its open enrollment period from November 13 to December 12, 2023.
To learn more about TRICARE Open Season, available options, and eligibility, Sarah Bumgardner, AAFMAA Director of Partnerships and Member Engagement, spoke with Amy Marotto, AAFMAA Member Benefits Team Lead.
Marotto is responsible for training AAFMAA’s Member Benefits team on military, government, and survivor benefits.
Prior to joining AAFMAA, Marotto was an educator for 20 years.
She received her MS in Education from Stephen F. Austin State University and a BS in Education from the University of North Texas.
text:
TRICARE, a comprehensive healthcare program available to active and former servicemembers and their families, is offering its open enrollment period from November 13 to December 12, 2023. During this time, if you are eligible, you can make changes to your plan.

To learn more about TRICARE Open Season, available options, and eligibility, Sarah Bumgardner, AAFMAA Director of Partnerships and Member Engagement, spoke with Amy Marotto, AAFMAA Member Benefits Team Lead. Marotto is responsible for training AAFMAA’s Member Benefits team on military, government, and survivor benefits. Prior to joining AAFMAA, Marotto was an educator for 20 years. She received her MS in Education from Stephen F. Austin State University and a BS in Education from the University of North Texas. Marotto is married to an active-duty U.S. Army officer, and they have two grown children and two grandchildren.

title: $171 for a 5-night hospital stay & C-Section!! (Tricare Select) : r/AirForce - Reddit
description:
Especially those you came in straight from HS.
My wife has a health-care option from work and honestly the only improvement would be dental/vision coverage.
30+ days in NICQ with wife staying 5 days because it was a high risk.
One wrong slip or procedure out of coverage or not covered and you can be incumbered with life changing debt.
Now we’re fighting to get them to pay 1000 dollars with a new backdated one we got put in.
text:
Something I think people just do not understand. Especially those you came in straight from HS.

My wife has a health-care option from work and honestly the only improvement would be dental/vision coverage.

We had twins at 33 weeks via c-section. 30+ days in NICQ with wife staying 5 days because it was a high risk. Half million dollar bill and didn't pay jack shit.

One wrong slip or procedure out of coverage or not covered and you can be incumbered with life changing debt.

Just make sure to keep up with the referral. We had an issue with the whole triwest ending all referrals because they ended a waiver period. Now we’re fighting to get them to pay 1000 dollars with a new backdated one we got put in.

title: Theresa Carpenter, APRᐩM's Post - LinkedIn
description:
✨ Fair Care for Every Military Family ✨ Military families face a healthcare burden most Americans never encounter.
Continued coverage can cost up to $727 per month through TRICARE Young Adult.
Military families already shoulder frequent moves, deployments, and complex medical needs.
🤝 Our nation asks a great deal of military families.
👉 Read more blog here: https://lnkd.in/g2ykFvdS #MilitaryFamilies #TRICARE #HealthcareEquity #VeteranAdvocacy #MilitaryKids #PolicyChange #SupportOurTroops #HealthCareReform
text: ✨ Fair Care for Every Military Family ✨ Military families face a healthcare burden most Americans never encounter. While civilian young adults can remain on their parents’ insurance until age 26, military dependents are forced off TRICARE at 21 (or 23 if full-time students). Continued coverage can cost up to $727 per month through TRICARE Young Adult. ⚕️💸 These costs don’t come from poor planning—they come from service. Military families already shoulder frequent moves, deployments, and complex medical needs. Adding thousands of dollars in annual healthcare premiums forces impossible choices: delaying education, accepting jobs solely for insurance, or taking on unnecessary debt. 🇺🇸 The Health Care Fairness for Military Families Act offers a straightforward fix by extending TRICARE coverage to age 26—aligning military healthcare with civilian standards. The legislation has bipartisan support and backing from major military and veterans organizations, reflecting a broad consensus that this gap is both unfair and unnecessary. 🤝 Our nation asks a great deal of military families. Ensuring equal access to healthcare is a basic step toward keeping that promise. 👉 Read more blog here: https://lnkd.in/g2ykFvdS #MilitaryFamilies #TRICARE #HealthcareEquity #VeteranAdvocacy #MilitaryKids #PolicyChange #SupportOurTroops #HealthCareReform

title: Tricare Dental : r/MilitarySpouse - Reddit
description:
If you have coverage through United Concordia(it’s a separate enrollment), then you need your sponsors name, the dependent ID number and the benefits number from the back of your mil ID.
You just let them know at the dental office you have united Concordia through TRICARE.
Go to the Tricare Dental Program website and find the list of in network dentists.
Then call the dental office to verify that they are still in network and make an appointment.
This won’t affect your dental coverage, but if you moved you should update your address with DEERS.
text:
If you have coverage through United Concordia(it’s a separate enrollment), then you need your sponsors name, the dependent ID number and the benefits number from the back of your mil ID. You just let them know at the dental office you have united Concordia through TRICARE.

And I do believe zip code changes from PCSing are subject to special enrollment outside of open enrollment(up to 30 days from when move was initiated). So if you need to change any coverage(like switching from prime to select, adding vision), now’s the time to do it.

Go to the Tricare Dental Program website and find the list of in network dentists. Then call the dental office to verify that they are still in network and make an appointment. You will have some out of pocket expenses for a wisdom teeth removal.

This won’t affect your dental coverage, but if you moved you should update your address with DEERS. You can use MilConnect. If you’re on Prime, that’s especially important so you can switch to a local PCM.
